## 2. Sustainable Transportation

### 2.1 Reduce Car Use and Opt for Low-Emission Alternatives

Transportation is a major source of greenhouse gas emissions. Living car-free or reducing car use can save approximately 2.4 tonnes of CO2 equivalent per year ([Wynes & Nicholas, 2017](https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1748-9326/aa7541)). When driving is necessary, adopting fuel-efficient driving habits and maintaining vehicles improves efficiency.

| Action                     | Estimated CO2 Savings (tonnes/year) |
|----------------------------|------------------------------------|
| Living car-free             | 2.4                                |
| Carpooling (one extra passenger) | Significant reduction in traffic and emissions |
| Using public transit        | Varies, generally lower than private car use |
| Biking or walking          | Near zero emissions                 |

### 2.2 Avoid Air Travel

Air travel is highly emission-intensive, contributing about 5% of global warming ([People's Climate March, 2017](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Individual_action_on_climate_change)). Avoiding flights, especially frequent long-distance trips, can reduce an individual's carbon footprint by 1.6 tonnes CO2 equivalent per roundtrip transatlantic flight ([Wynes & Nicholas, 2017](https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1748-9326/aa7541)).

**Alternatives:**
- Use trains or buses for short to medium distances.
- Combine trips to reduce the number of flights.
- Offset unavoidable flights through verified carbon offset programs.

